text: Gather tinder and kindling. Create a bird's nest structure around your tinder. Ignite tinder and gradually add fuel sticks when flames rise.

Take time to select a safe spot for a shelter. For example, don’t build one on the top of a hill or in a dry river bed. Don’t camp in a clearing where you may be the tallest object and a target of lightning. Look and make sure that there are not any dead trees nearby that could fall over in a storm or strong winds. When building a shelter, the smaller the better. Many individuals try to build a bigger shelter than they need. A smaller shelter traps your body heat better than a big shelter, and it takes less time to build. If selecting a natural shelter like a cave, make sure it is not a home to a wild animal. Throw rocks inside, etc. Look for signs of wildlife in and around the cave before entering. Avoid building a shelter right next to a lake or game trail. Be very careful when constructing a snow cave, as cave ins and asphyxiation are real threats.

Pick an area with 2 good trees or objects to tie a line to. Check the area for dead trees that could fall on you. Clear the area of sticks and small rocks that could make sleeping uncomfortable. Tie your Taught line with your paracord. First tie your static hitch. Then tie your movable truckers hitch. Drape tarp over the taught line. Tie a double hitch to rocks and then to the corners of your tarp to hold down the ends (if you do not have eyelets on your tarp you can use a ghost hitch — see below). Move the rocks until the walls of your shelter are tight. If needed, add more rocks to the corners to make sure they don’t move even in high winds.

Prevention Tips:
- Wear properly fitting boots.
- Use padding and sock liners to reduce friction.
- Tape any sore spots.
- Tighten boots before downhill movements.

Clean well with an antiseptic wipe. Sterilize the point of a pin or knife with flame or analcohol swab and gently pierce the blister. Massage the fluid out, leaving the roof of the blister intact. Cover with a friction-reducing dressing by cutting a donut-shaped piece of moleskinand place it over the blister. Fill the hole with antibiotic ointment and cover the moleskin with athletic or duct tape.

Immediately plunge the burn site into cold water. Second best: Apply a water-soaked bandanna, a burn gel, or aloe vera. Continue cooling until pain has substantially subsided, then cover the burn with ointment and a gauze pad. If the blisters form, prevent the blisters from popping as long as possible.

Scrub the wound with soap and a gauze pad or bandanna, making sure to remove all debris (warning: It'll hurt). Rinse off all of the soap, then apply a layer of antibiotic ointment to a gauze pad and tape it in place. (You can also use a commercial pad with adhesive edges.) The pad should completely cover the wound.

topic: Applying a Moist Dressing for Burns
text:
1. Clean the burn area.
2. Dampen clean cloth dressings.
3. Apply to less than 10% of total body surface area.
4. Maintain dampness without soaking.
5. Manage shock and keep the patient calm.

Remember RICE: First, rest. Ice the site to reduce swelling (use snow or cold water). After 20 to 30 minutes, remove the cold and let the injured area warm naturally for 10 to 15 minutes before use. Compress the injury with elastic wrap or athletic tape (the basket-weave pattern, right, works well for ankle sprains).
Apply it snugly, but not tight enough to cut off circulation, and wrap it toward the heart (for example, up the leg, not down). Elevate the injury by keeping it higher than the heart. Repeat three to four times a day until pain and swelling subside.

If the stinger remains in the skin, remove it immediately. Apply a cold pack for pain and swelling, and give an oral antihistamine. If the patient has an allergic reaction–difficulty breathing, tightness of the chest, swelling of the throat, dizziness–give a dose of injectable epinephrine (prescription required) and the antihistamine. Evacuate to medical attention ASAP, keeping a second dose of epi on hand and giving more antihistamine every four to six hours.

These bloodsuckers can transmit disease if allowed to embed in the skin (sometimes a few hours is all it takes), so check yourself twice a day. Found one? Remove it immediately with tweezers. Grasp the tick at skin level, perpendicular to the long axis of the tick, and pull it gently straight out. Wash the site. If illness and/or an unusual rash develop, consult a doctor.

Black widow bites can be tough to diagnose (many victims don't feel the bite when it occurs). Look for vomiting, weakness, headache, fever, and intense abdominal and/or back pain. Brown recluse bites might sting or itch. For both, clean the wound, apply cold to the site, and give the patient an antihistamine (for itching) and ibuprofen for pain. Hike out to a doctor (don't worry: death is rare).

First, keep the victim calm (a low heart rate minimizes venom circulation, and death from snakebite is unlikely). Remove jewelry, watches, and any snug clothing that could cut off circulation when the bite site swells. Splint the bitten arm or leg, but do not elevate it. Carry the victim out if you can; otherwise, have him slowly walk out for a dose of antivenin.

Stop the bleeding. Immediately wash the wound thoroughly with soap and water. Rinse clean, cover with a sterile dressing smeared with antibacterial ointment, and find a doctor ASAP. These bites have a high risk of infection, including rabies–and in that case, the victim needs a vaccination within 72 hours for the best chance of survival.

In all cases, give lots of fluids to prevent dehydration and pop an Imodium AD tablet. For more severe diarrhea, add electrolyte tablets, such as NUUN, to the water. Give him easily digested foods (such as rice or oatmeal); avoid fats, dairy products, and caffeine. If it's not under control within 24 hours, find a doctor–sooner if bloody bowel movements, fever, and pain exist.
Give as much fluid as the patient can tolerate and have him rest–but evacuate if the problem persists for more than 24 hours.

Rinse your mouth with a solution of half a teaspoon of salt and eight ounces of water several times a day. If pain, sensitivity to hot and cold, and swelling exist, get to a doctor–it could be an abcess.

Rinse the tooth thoroughly with drinking water, then protect the sensitive nerve by placing a chewed piece of gum over the break. Apply a cold-water bladder to the patient's cheek to reduce swelling, and take ibuprofen for the pain. Hike out to your dentist.
The person complains of feeling cold and shivers. More advanced hypothermia patients exhibit the umbles: stumbling, fumbling, mumbling, and grumbling.

Get the patient into warm, dry clothes and place him in a sheltered area–such as in a sleeping bag, inside of a tent. (Don't have a tent? Protect him from the elements by wrapping the sleeping bag in a tarp, plastic sheet, or garbage bags.) Give water and simple sugars, such as hot chocolate or candy, to generate quick body heat. For more advanced cases, build a fire nearby and put the patient in a "hypothermia wrap:" Start with a sleeping pad, put a zipped sleeping bag on top, then lay the patient (in a second sleeping bag) on that. Give him a hot-water bottle wrapped in clothing to hold in his hands. Put another sleeping bag on top, then wrap it all, burrito-style, in a tarp or plastic sheet.

Look for chest pain that radiates to the shoulder, arm, or jaw (especially on the left side), nausea, lightheadedness, and pale, cool, sweaty skin. Keep the person comfortably at rest, cover him with clothing or a sleeping bag to prevent heat loss, and keep him as calm as possible. Give an aspirin tablet (to inhibit artery-clogging blood clots). Don't let the person walk. Get help.

Look for rapid, weak pulse; shallow breathing; clammy skin; and nausea. Caused by an inadequate flow of oxygenated blood, shock can result from any major injury, including blood loss, severe dehydration, and spinal cord damage. If the cause can be treated–such as rehydrating the dehydrated–do it. Put him in a sleeping bag or cover him with extra clothing. Keep the person calm and lying down on a sleeping pad with his legs comfortably elevated about 10 inches. If vital signs don't improve with treatment or the patient becomes less responsive, go for help. Left untreated, shock can be fatal.

Move the person as little as possible (if movement is necessary, don't bend or twist the spine). Place a SAM splint around the neck to restrict the head. Do not leave the patient alone. Have someone keep a hand on the person's head to discourage movement. Go for help.

Treat all unknown mushrooms as deadly–the bad ones are that bad. Induce vomiting as soon as possible after ingestion by having him stick a finger down his throat to stimulate the gag reflex. Give plenty of fluids to dilute the poison, keep a sample of the mushroom, and get to a doctor. Poisoning symptoms take six to 24 hours to appear–and by then, it's often too late.

A blow to the head that results in unconsciousness often causes the brain to swell. Early signs include progressive disorientation, irritability, and combativeness (after consciousness returns). Evacuate the patient immediately. If he's unconscious, carefully roll him onto his side and go for help.
Eat two teaspoons of menthol toothpaste mixed with cold water.

Use honey to discourage infection and promote healing. (it's a natural antibacterial agent). Spread it over the surface of minor cuts, burns, abrasions, and frostbite (but not directly in a wound) and cover with gauze.
Cut a thin strip of fabric out of a T-shirt (snip in a circular pattern around the shirt to get the longest dressing possible).

No SAM splint? Roll a bulky jacket or fleece, leaving the sleeves out, and wrap it around the patient's neck (see left). Tie it in place with the sleeves. Or cut a foam pad into a collar and tape it in place.
Soak the injury in cold water, or wrap soaked bandannas or cotton T-shirts around the site.

Pull the bottom of the patient's short-sleeve shirt up and over the injured arm and pin it to the front with two safety pins. Long-sleeve shirt? Pin the sleeve of the injured arm (with the arm in it) to the shirt.

Injuries in the wild can heighten stress levels. It's vital to remain calm:
- Take deep breaths and create an immediate action plan.
- Assign roles within your group to manage the situation effectively.
- Keep communication clear and engage the injured party when appropriate.

Be aware of the risk of infection when providing first aid:
- Check for open wounds on yourself before helping others.
- Use nitrile gloves and protective gear when possible.
- If those aren’t available, improvise using materials on hand.

One person should lead during an emergency to reduce confusion:
- Follow the designated leader or take charge if no leader exists.
- Delegate tasks to team members, such as organizing evacuation and calming the injured.

description: A classic and secure loop knot that is easy to untie. Tie a loop in the end of a line. It doesn’t slip when it is loaded but will untie easily when not loaded.
use_cases: securing a rope to a post
tie a bear bag from the loop at the end of a hanging rope
instructions:
1. Make a small loop (the 'rabbit hole').
2. Bring the working end ('the rabbit') up through the hole.
3. Wrap the working end around the standing part ('the tree').
4. Bring the working end back down through the small loop.
5. Tighten the knot.

description: Used to tie two ends of a rope together of equal thickness. Not suitable for heavy loads.
use_cases: tie up a bundle of wood
extend the length of a washing line by tying two ropes together
instructions:
1. Take the two rope ends.
2. Pass the right end over the left end, and then under it.
3. Take the same end (which is now on the left) and pass it over the other end (which is now on the right).
4. Pass it under the other end.
5. Pull both standing ends to tighten. (Mnemonic: 'Right over left and under, left over right and under').

description: Used to tie two ropes together that are different sizes or thicknesses. The thicker rope must be used as the bight with the thinner rope tying around it
use_cases: lengthen a guy line by adding a spare bit of rope or string to the end
fix snapped boot laces by adding whatever bit of string or cord you can get hold of
instructions:
1. Form a bight (a 'U' shape) in the end of the thicker rope.
2. Pass the working end of the thinner rope up through the bight from underneath.
3. Wrap the thinner rope around the entire bight (both strands of the thicker rope).
4. Tuck the working end of the thinner rope back under itself (where it first came through the bight).
5. Ensure both working ends are on the same side of the knot. Pull tight.

knot_name: Round turn and two half hitches
description: Used to secure a rope in a variety of situations. A good all round hitch that is strong and doesn’t slip.
use_cases: tie a washing line to a tree
tie a load to a tree branch
securing a boat to a post
instructions:
1. Pass the working end of the rope around the post or tree twice. This is the 'round turn'.
2. Bring the working end over the standing part of the rope.
3. Pass the working end through the loop you just created. This is the first 'half hitch'.
4. Tie a second half hitch in the same way (over the standing part and through the new loop).
5. Pull the knot tight against the round turn.

description: Used to: create a loop in the end or middle of a rope. It is easy to identify if done incorrectly and is a strong knot that tightens with a load.
use_cases: create a line with multiple loops to hang things on
instructions:
1. Double the rope to form a bight (a loop).
2. Pass the bight over the standing part to create a loop (like the start of a figure eight).
3. Continue wrapping the bight around the standing part.
4. Pass the bight down through the initial loop you created.
5. Pull to tighten, ensuring the '8' shape is clear and the loops are parallel.

description: Used to: create an adjustable knot that can slide back and forth along a line. It is a secure knot as long as there is tension
instructions:
1. Wrap the working end around the standing line (or object).
2. Make two wraps with the working end *inside* the loop you've formed, working back towards the start.
3. Make one more wrap *outside* the first two wraps (closer to the standing part).
4. Pass the working end through this third loop to form a half hitch.
5. Tighten the knot. It should now slide when pushed but grip when pulled.

text: Look up first. Never build under large, dead trees or hanging, broken branches. These are "widowmakers" that can fall in a storm or from rot. Stay near a water source (for drinking), but not too close. Avoid dry riverbeds, ravines, or low-lying areas that are obvious flash flood zones. Look for tell-tale signs like piles of debris washed up against trees. Select flat, high ground that will drain well. Avoid exposed ridges. Build on a slightly sheltered spot, and orient the opening of your shelter away from the prevailing wind to prevent rain from blowing inside. Choose a spot with an abundant supply of building materials (bamboo, poles, fallen branches, and large-leafed plants) to minimize energy-wasting travel.

topic: Building a Basic Shelter (Raised Platform Bed)
text: Getting your body off the damp, leech-infested, and insect-covered jungle floor is essential. This is your first priority. Find Four Y-Posts: Cut four strong, sturdy branches, each with a "Y" shape at the top. They should all be the same height, ideally at least 1-2 feet (0.5m) tall. Set the Corners: Drive these four posts firmly into the ground in a rectangle, wide enough and long enough for you to lie down on. Create the Frame: Find two long, straight, and strong poles. Lay these "support poles" into the Y-shaped notches on the head and foot of the bed. Lay the Platform: Find many thinner, straight poles (spars). Lay these across the two support poles to create your sleeping surface. Leave small, finger-width gaps between them—this is more comfortable than a solid surface, especially for side-sleeping, and improves airflow. Add a "Mattress": Cover the platform with a thick layer of large, broad leaves (like banana or palm fronds) to create a softer, insulated bed.

topic: The Quick Tarp Shelter (If Have a Tarp/Poncho)
text: This is the fastest and most practical option. The key is to pitch it high for ventilation and create a separate sleeping platform. Find Trees: Locate two trees 8-10 feet apart. Create a Ridgeline: Run a rope (or strong vine) between the two trees, about 4-5 feet off the ground. Pitch the Roof: Drape your tarp or poncho over the ridgeline, creating an "A-frame" shape. Stake it Out: Pull the corners of the tarp down and stake them to the ground, or tie them to smaller bushes or heavy rocks. Crucially, leave a gap of 1-2 feet between the ground and the tarp's edge to allow for airflow. Build a Bed: Find four sturdy, Y-shaped branches. Hammer them into the ground to form a rectangle under the tarp. Lay two long, strong poles across the Y-sticks to create side rails. Place many smaller, straight sticks (bamboo is ideal) across the side rails to form your bed platform. Cover the platform with a thick layer of large leaves (like banana or palm fronds) for a mattress.

topic: The Natural Raised A-Frame Shelter (Full Survival)
text:
Needed Items: Strong, straight poles (bamboo is perfect if available). Thinner, straight sticks for the platform. An abundant supply of large leaves (palm fronds, banana leaves, ginger leaves). Flexible vines, rattan, or strips of fibrous bark to tie the frame together.
Instructions: Look for a level spot on slightly higher ground to avoid pooling water. A small clearing that gets a breeze is ideal. This is your priority. Hammer four strong, Y-shaped posts (at least 2-3 feet tall) into the ground to form the corners of your bed. Lay two long, load-bearing poles into the "Y" grooves on each side. Lay a dense platform of thinner, cross-member sticks on top. Lash them together if you can. Pile on a thick "mattress" of leaves and ferns for comfort. Find a long, straight pole for your ridgeline. Prop up the ridgeline directly over the center of your bed using two "A"-shaped frames at the head and foot. Alternatively, you can rest the ridgeline pole in the Y-fork of two nearby trees, but building the "A" frames gives you more control over location. Lean long, straight sticks from the ground up to your ridgeline pole, angling them at about 45-60 degrees. A steeper roof sheds rain better. Place these "rafters" every 1-2 feet along both sides of the ridgeline. Start from the bottom and work your way up. This is critical. Gather your large leaves (palm fronds are best). Lay the first layer of leaves along the very bottom of the rafters. Place the second layer overlapping the first, like shingles on a house. Continue this process, overlapping each new layer over the one below it, all the way to the top. When you reach the ridgeline (the peak), lay an extra-thick layer of leaves over the top and weigh them down with a pole to prevent leaks. The water will now run down each leaf, onto the leaf below it, and all the way to the ground.
